{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b6b8158-a9ce-49bd-8f3e-46d94efe1888","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there's no request pipeline — the default DI scope lives for the **entire application lifetime**. So `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext (with its change tracker) persists across navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new DbContext each time one is injected.\n2. **Create scopes manually** using `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n3. **Clear the change tracker** when navigating:\n   ```csharp\n   dbContext.ChangeTracker.Clear();\n   ```\n\n`AddTransient` is the simplest drop-in fix for most MAUI scenarios.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b323391f-a2e3-43d8-b777-cfd6ebf5cfea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, \"scoped\" means per-HTTP-request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so \"scoped\" effectively behaves like a singleton — the scope lives for the entire app lifetime. That's why their DbContext persists across navigations.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"4834:DE08:7961FAF:85B66A8:69F3FD0E"},"id":"35fb553b-c6dd-4d23-b252-215054fea812","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:08:39.183Z","parentId":"03d7e81d-8e7b-45dc-b0c0-dea5997c989e"}
